<seg id="1">Winston Churchill, an all-American hero</seg>
<seg id="2">This week, the elite of American politics gathered in Washington DC to unveil a bust of Winston Churchill at the Capitol building.</seg>
<seg id="3">The rotunda where he now sits immortalised in bronze, and looking a little perplexed, was renamed the Freedom Foyer for the occasion.</seg>
<seg id="4">John Kerry, the Secretary of State, listened as John Boehner, the leader of the House Republicans, gave a passionate speech of dedication.</seg>
<seg id="5">"Ladies and gentlemen," said Mr Boehner, "this is one of history's true love stories."</seg>
<seg id="6">"Between a great statesman and a nation he called 'The Great Republic." " The famously sentimental Republican wiped tears from his eyes as the crowd listened to a recording of Churchill addressing Congress following the attack on Pearl Harbor in 1941.</seg>
<seg id="7">Afterwards, Roger Daltrey of The Who sang Stand by Me - a tribute, Mr Boehner said, to "the best friend the United States ever had."</seg>
<seg id="8">Americans heard Churchill's war broadcasts - and it's this image of resolution and pluck that stayed with them throughout the Second World War, and beyond.</seg>
<seg id="9">After Germany's defeat, and thrown out of office by Labour's surprise 1945 election victory, Churchill leant moral leadership to the fight with Soviet Communism.</seg>
<seg id="10">On March 5, 1946, he gave a speech before 40,000 at the small town of Fulton, Missouri, in which he declared: "From Stettin in the Baltic to Trieste in the Adriatic, an iron curtain has descended across the Continent."</seg>
<seg id="11">This was the rhetorical starting gun for the Cold War.</seg>
<seg id="12">The simplest reason why Churchill is so popular in the US is that he was an ally in three global wars.</seg>
<seg id="13">Of course, we must not be seduced by myth; profound differences between the interests of Britain and US remained.</seg>
<seg id="14">When Churchill was returned as prime minister in 1951, he inherited a number of small conflicts between British and American interests in both the South Seas and the Middle East (the latter culminating in the 1956 Suez crisis).</seg>
<seg id="15">What is more, wherever the US helped Britain, it inevitably supplanted its power.</seg>
<seg id="16">The alliance evolved from being a collaboration between brothers to something resembling a master leading its poodle by the leash.</seg>
<seg id="17">Americans can look back with misty eyes on the Churchill era because that's when the US empire took over from the British one.</seg>
<seg id="18">Indeed, there are two big reasons why Americans obsess over Churchill that aren't entirely about the man himself.</seg>
<seg id="19">First, he is a reminder of a time when many Americans felt supremely confident about their role in the world.</seg>
<seg id="20">The 1940s and 1950s mixed economic growth with taking the lead against totalitarianism overseas, creating a conservative Golden Age, when the American Way meant something.</seg>
<seg id="21">I stress that it was a "conservative" Golden Age, because it is notable how much larger Churchill looms in the minds of the Right than he does the Left.</seg>
<seg id="22">I asked John Bolton, George W Bush's ambassador to the UN during the Iraq War, what qualities made Churchill so appealing to Americans and he ranked "strength of conviction" highly.</seg>
<seg id="23">His views on appeasement in the 1930s were unpopular but he stood by them and was vindicated.</seg>
<seg id="24">So we associate him with someone who stood by his views, with the defeat of the Nazis in World War II and being a staunch anti-Communist... It's about his strength of leadership.</seg>
<seg id="25">It's unsurprising that in that "most admired leader" poll of CEOs, the only woman who made it into the Top 10 was Margaret Thatcher - another British leader who is renowned for being a conviction politician.</seg>
<seg id="26">Leading by sheer strength of individual will is unusual in Britain, where, arguably, we have historically preferred consensus and moderation.</seg>
<seg id="27">Churchill and Thatcher appeal more broadly to the American conservative taste for shooting first and asking questions later.</seg>
<seg id="28">All Americans love learning about how to lead.</seg>
<seg id="29">Google "Churchill" and "leadership" and you'll find several books on how to succeed in business the Winston way.</seg>
<seg id="30">Steven F Hayward's Churchill on Leadership: Executive Success in the Face of Adversity carries the blurb, "With wit and insight, Hayward reveals Churchill's secrets for business success from assembling and inspiring a first-rate team to preparing a wise budget, from communicating a vision to structuring effective meetings, from acting decisively to rebounding from a failure."</seg>
<seg id="31">There's nothing unusual in this - you can purchase guides on how to run your laundry firm like Reagan or Lincoln.</seg>
<seg id="32">What it speaks to is the American Dream's emphasis upon individual success, and the constant search for guidance from great men on how to make friends and influence people - taking lessons from history and using them to make money.</seg>
<seg id="33">The ghost of Churchill is not unlike a motivational speaker or a lifestyle guru.</seg>
<seg id="34">To return to the unveiling of the Churchill bust in the Freedom Foyer, many of the politicians gathered probably fancy themselves as mini-Winstons in the making and have probably studied his life and wisdom in vain hope of becoming just as great.</seg>
<seg id="35">Vain, because it's impossible to replicate an individual's charisma.</seg>
<seg id="36">And vain, also, because Churchill was actually the product of a time and place far removed from the modern America that admires him so - aristocratic and proudly (even eccentrically) English.</seg>
<seg id="37">That said, the famously wet political class of Washington DC wouldn't struggle to match his prowess with drink.</seg>
<seg id="38">It is said that between 1908 and 1965, Churchill drank 42,000 bottles of champagne.</seg>
<seg id="39">That's a record that most US senators could happily match.</seg>
