<seg id="1">Even passed-in properties are in hot demand</seg>
<seg id="2">Adam Elmasri is selling his childhood home in Elwood.</seg>
<seg id="3">Chris Scott Source: News Limited</seg>
<seg id="4">MELBOURNE'S auction market is even hotter than reported with research revealing eight out of 10 properties are selling under the hammer or shortly afterwards.</seg>
<seg id="5">The RP Data Auction Plus research - exclusive to the Herald Sun - reveals the auction clearance rate, trending at 71 per cent, is 13 per cent higher when properties sold within 30 days after auction are included.</seg>
<seg id="6">"Auction Plus looks at the success rate of the auction process rather than the auction result on the day," said RP Data analyst Cameron Kusher.</seg>
<seg id="7">Even if property is not successful at the auction - although most are currently - they are gathering quite a lot of attention and negotiations in the majority of cases are resulting in a quick sale afterwards.</seg>
<seg id="8">The traditional increase in listings for spring has not slowed sales.</seg>
<seg id="9">Mr Kusher said the number of new listings on the market nationally is 4.3 per cent higher this year.</seg>
<seg id="10">But strong buyer demand means listings in Melbourne are 10 per cent lower than last year as older stock also sells.</seg>
<seg id="11">The average time on market has also fallen from 55 days at this time last year to 44 days at the moment.</seg>
<seg id="12">Despite a clearance rate of 72 per cent hundreds of properties were passed in as a record 1614 properties went under the hammer last weekend.</seg>
<seg id="13">Among them was Adam Elmasri's childhood home in Elwood, though he and sales agent Martin Fox, from Wilson Real Estate, are confident it will sell quickly.</seg>
<seg id="14">"You never know what will happen on the day, but it's a great property," Mr Elmasri said.</seg>
<seg id="15">Mr Fox is now targeting buyers who missed out at auction last weekend.</seg>
<seg id="16">"It does depend on the property, a larger property like this can take a month," he said.</seg>
<seg id="17">Andrew James, an auctioneer with Hocking Stuart, which accounted for more than 10 per cent of Melbourne's record event last weekend, said the spring market was ripe for auctions.</seg>
<seg id="18">"In the market just recently it has been about a week (after auction) that we have been able to secure the sale," he said.</seg>
