<seg id="1">Carole King, what a Natural Woman</seg>
<seg id="2">Carole King performing in Perth earlier this month: Thomas Davidson Source: PerthNow</seg>
<seg id="3">CAROLE King fans at the Adelaide Festival Centre last night certainly felt the earth move under their feet as the powerhouse vocalist delivered a flawless show crammed with hits, passion and emotion.</seg>
<seg id="4">The 71 year old was ageless as she took to the modestly adorned stage to belt out her back catalogue of hits that spanned from 1960 through to present day.</seg>
<seg id="5">It was clear to see why King has enjoyed the career longevity she currently boasts - she gives her all on stage and is pure talent.</seg>
<seg id="6">Opening with Home Again, King then led the capacity crowd through her hits as well as some songs she and ex-husband Gerry Goffin penned for other successful artists.</seg>
<seg id="7">Conveying a warmth, wit and credibility that is immediately endearing it's easy to see why so many artists clamored to work with King and, now, tour with her.</seg>
<seg id="8">Her on-stage cohorts were nothing short of spectacular - King allowed her two very talented back-up singers to shine in their own right on several occasions and her guitarist's solos perfectly complemented King's unique vocal.</seg>
<seg id="9">But it was her hits from 1971's Tapestry that got the biggest cheers of the night, among them I Feel the Earth Move, It's Too Late, Will You Love Me Tomorrow? and Way Over Yonder.</seg>
<seg id="10">However the diminutive singer - who really does use her effortless vocal as the ultimate instrument - truly left the best for last, wrapping the show with a three song encore showcasing that iconic album's biggest hits - So Far Away, (You Make Me Feel Like) A Natural Woman and You've Got A Friend.</seg>
<seg id="11">Unsurprisingly King left the Festival Centre stage to a rousing standing ovation and many hoping her return to our shores won't be so far away.</seg>
</doc>
