<seg id="1">Home, Arcola Theatre, review - Telegraph</seg>
<seg id="2">Two gentle old boys, Harry and Jack, meet in a garden and pass the time with wittering chit-chat.</seg>
<seg id="3">They talk in non sequiturs, spouting scattergun tidbits of information they've picked up over the years.</seg>
<seg id="4">The best musicians have curly hair.</seg>
<seg id="5">Hot climates can be difficult.</seg>
<seg id="6">Money intrudes on emotion.</seg>
<seg id="7">They're like two cultural anthropologists swapping field notes; two talking editions of Schott's Miscellany.</seg>
<seg id="8">Now, in this intimate fringe revival to mark the playwright's 80th birthday, Jack Shepherd and Paul Copley play the pair with glazed expressions and sunny dispositions.</seg>
<seg id="9">It's curious that Storey specifies fortysomethings, but always gets actors in their sixties.</seg>
<seg id="10">With death hovering somewhere high overhead, you wonder what all this information's good for.</seg>
<seg id="11">These men don't actually communicate; neither really listens.</seg>
<seg id="12">They're like Beckett characters sewn into the real world: absurd, but not absurdly so.</seg>
<seg id="13">All they have is time to kill: "One of the advantages of a late lunch," muses Jack, "is that it leaves a shorter space to tea."</seg>
<seg id="14">Storey reveals, ever so slowly and carefully, that the garden sits in the grounds of a mental institution.</seg>
<seg id="15">The penny should drop as if through treacle, but director Amelia Sears lets go too early, when two women saunter in under an umbrella so moth-eaten it's basically all holes.</seg>
<seg id="16">It shatters the play's delicate ambiguity, its ability to pass for everyday life, and so punctures the potency of its metaphor, which is both broadly existential and directly national.</seg>
<seg id="17">These old girls are working class and bawdy.</seg>
<seg id="18">Kathleen (Linda Broughton) explodes at every double entendre; Majorie (Tessa Peake-Jones) has a malicious edge.</seg>
<seg id="19">Harry and Jack like to think themselves worldly, but they're no match for these women, and still less for the pent-up young man (Joseph Arkley) rampaging through the garden, tossing patio furniture around like St Jude's storm.</seg>
<seg id="20">Storey shows Middle England as only too civil, but all too ineffectual.</seg>
<seg id="21">However, Sears's production benefits no end from its intimacy, with the audience perched on benches around the patio, itself another gorgeously natural Naomi Dawson design that's well-served by Richard Howell's lazy afternoon lighting.</seg>
<seg id="22">Proximity allows Shepherd and Copley to become ever so unassuming in their child-like chatterings, while making Arkley's lobotomised Alfred all the more imposing.</seg>
<seg id="23">Until Nov 23.</seg>
<seg id="24">Tickets: 020 7503 1646; arcolatheatre.com</seg>
</doc>
