<doc docid="2d105e98e3bfbb21955a3bd880a230a3" genre="news" origlang="xx">
<seg id="1">touched by the power of art</seg>
<seg id="2">Sculptures by the Sea by touch</seg>
<seg id="3">"Tactile Tour" of the Sculptures by the Sea exhibition, which has been designed specifically to offer people with a disability new ways of experiencing and enjoying contemporary sculpture.</seg>
<seg id="4">PT3M48Shttp://www.smh.com.au/action/externalEmbeddedPlayer?id=d-2wmx9620349November 1, 2013 - 10:20PM</seg>
<seg id="5">Max Brodie lifts his white cane and runs it around the contours of a metal sculpture.</seg>
<seg id="6">Glaucoma has robbed him of much of his sight, but he can still see colours - the golden sand, the blue of the sky - and the shapes and shadows cast by exhibits at Sculpture by the Sea.</seg>
<seg id="7">Touching the sculptures, and hearing descriptions from a volunteer guide from the Art Gallery of NSW, allowed him to experience the art on display.</seg>
<seg id="8">Sensory experience: A group of visually impaired art lovers enjoy a tour of the exhibits at Sculpture by the Sea.</seg>
<seg id="9">Photo: Dallas Kilponen</seg>
<seg id="10">Mr Brodie, 86, was one of six visually impaired people who visited Tamarama beach this week on a trip organised by Guide Dogs NSW/ACT.</seg>
<seg id="11">After feeling their way around the sculptures they took part in a pilot workshop, creating their own sculpture with the help of exhibiting artist Jane Gillings.</seg>
<seg id="12">She said sculpture was a good art form for the vision impaired, being "very hands on."</seg>
<seg id="13">Ying-Wah Wan, an orientation and mobility instructor with Guide Dogs NSW/ACT, said "the added sense of touch gives [the art] a different meaning" for her clients, while creating their own sculpture "has been a great opportunity to demonstrate that vision loss doesn't have to limit your independence or creativity."</seg>
<seg id="14">The group took public transport to the beach, with Mr Brodie saying it helped raise public awareness of white canes.</seg>
<seg id="15">People still don't understand what they are.</seg>
<seg id="16">So often people [say], 'Oh, you're going to play golf, are you?'</seg>
<seg id="17">Their visit was was part of the increasingly popular Sculpture by the Sea Tactile Tours program, giving people with disabilities the chance to enjoy contemporary sculpture.</seg>
<seg id="18">"It's a sensory experience," Sculpture by Sea's education manager, Petra Pattinson, said.</seg>
<seg id="19">It engages them; they really get involved in the texture, the shape.</seg>
<seg id="20">They'll spend quite a lot of time exploring what that work feels like.</seg>
</doc>
