<seg id="1">By Sir Michael Caine</seg>
<seg id="2">Mel Smith died three months ago with a dream unfulfilled.</seg>
<seg id="3">He was preparing to portray in a TV film the rumbustious London restaurateur Peter Langan, whose signature dish was insults.</seg>
<seg id="4">Night after night, Langan would lurch towards tables occupied by the rich, the famous and the royal in his fashionable brasserie just off Piccadilly and behave outrageously.</seg>
<seg id="5">Smith had been fascinated for years by the stories of Irish-born Langan's almost comic notoriety, and enjoyed it when people remarked on his physical resemblance.</seg>
<seg id="6">Man of the moment: Peter Langan, owned and ran Langan's Brasserie in London's Mayfair and was infamous for his drunken outbursts and outrageous behavior</seg>
<seg id="7">So he was thrilled when he was sent a script for a biopic to mark the 25th anniversary of Langan's bizarre death.</seg>
<seg id="8">But Smith's own death from a heart attack has put the TV film on hold.</seg>
<seg id="9">Meanwhile, Langan's legend lives on.</seg>
<seg id="10">Here, Sir Michael Caine who was his business partner, recalls how, in spite of Peter's excesses, Langan's became such a success:</seg>
<seg id="11">I was having a nice dinner at my usual window table in Langan's with my wife Shakira, our daughter and my mother when Peter Langan decided to join us.</seg>
<seg id="12">That was his style.</seg>
<seg id="13">He would plonk himself down at diners" tables, uninvited - usually unwelcome, sometimes entertaining, but never sober.</seg>
<seg id="14">I could see that Peter was the worse for wear.</seg>
<seg id="15">He and I were partners, but we hadn't been getting on very well lately, and he began making a nuisance of himself.</seg>
<seg id="16">Telling his story: Sir Michael Caine speaks - mostly - fond words of his friend Peter Langan</seg>
<seg id="17">I called over our other partner, the chef Richard Shepherd.</seg>
<seg id="18">"Tell Peter to leave my bloody table," I pleaded.</seg>
<seg id="19">Then my mum told me off for swearing!</seg>
<seg id="20">Richard tried to persuade him to come to the bar, but Peter refused.</seg>
<seg id="21">"I ain't going anywhere, kid," he replied.</seg>
<seg id="22">Tell Michael Caine to f*** off.</seg>
<seg id="23">Impasse.</seg>
<seg id="24">I said: "I can go anywhere I want."</seg>
<seg id="25">I don't have to come to Langan's to be insulted.</seg>
<seg id="26">Unless you leave my table, I am leaving.</seg>
<seg id="27">"Then f***ing leave," replied Peter.</seg>
<seg id="28">So I did.</seg>
<seg id="29">That was typical Peter.</seg>
<seg id="30">When in those moods, he insisted on addressing me by my real name, Maurice Micklewhite.</seg>
<seg id="31">He had this idea I was from a lower social order, and when he wanted to be insulting he described me as a "mediocrity with halitosis who has a council house mind."</seg>
<seg id="32">I'd retaliate by saying: "Peter stumbles around in a cloud of his own vomit and is a complete social embarrassment."</seg>
<seg id="33">You would have a more interesting conversation with a cabbage.</seg>
<seg id="34">But he did make me laugh, even if the other diners didn't always find him so funny.</seg>
<seg id="35">Princess Margaret and her young lover Roddy Llewellyn had enjoyed an intimate meal and were just at the coffee stage when Peter stumbled over.</seg>
<seg id="36">Mumbling incoherently, he took off his jacket and hung it on the back of Margaret's chair.</seg>
<seg id="37">Then he climbed on to the table - knocking cups and jugs of milk everywhere - and promptly fell asleep.</seg>
<seg id="38">Margaret was not amused.</seg>
<seg id="39">She and Roddy left, never to return.</seg>
<seg id="40">It wasn't his only brush with royalty.</seg>
<seg id="41">"Is it true you're a f***ing poof?" he once asked Prince Albert of Monaco.</seg>
<seg id="42">I always used to say that we could never bar anyone from Langan's because we'd have to start with Peter.</seg>
<seg id="43">Even so, he tried.</seg>
<seg id="44">He once barred Rudolf Nureyev "for being himself."</seg>
<seg id="45">He failed to recognise Marlon Brando, explaining: "The only thing I knew about him was that he is even fatter than me."</seg>
<seg id="46">And when Peter demanded to know why the restaurant had sent Ronnie Corbett a case of champagne, a furious Richard told him the truth.</seg>
<seg id="47">Because you insulted him, Peter.</seg>
<seg id="48">He might be small, but there was no need to tell him he's a f****** midget.</seg>
<seg id="49">When Peter was around, you had to be careful about having him meet your friends.</seg>
<seg id="50">Like the time I introduced him to Orson Welles.</seg>
<seg id="51">Was Peter impressed with one of cinema's greats?</seg>
<seg id="52">Not a bit.</seg>
<seg id="53">"I think you're a stupid fat ****," said Peter.</seg>
<seg id="54">A waiter grabbed him and hustled him away.</seg>
<seg id="55">That was the last time I introduced Peter to anyone.</seg>
<seg id="56">Just occasionally, some of our celebrity diners were made to feel welcome by Peter.</seg>
<seg id="57">Like the time he tried to carry Billy Connolly on a joyful lap of honour round the restaurant after the Big Yin had opened in the play The Beastly Beatitudes Of Balthazar B.</seg>
<seg id="58">Langan's Brasseries was opened in 1976 by Michael Caine and then unknown chef Peter Langan</seg>
<seg id="59">You'd wonder sometimes why some diners ever came back.</seg>
<seg id="60">Fuelled by a daily intake of a dozen bottles of champagne, as he liked to boast, he'd crawl under tables and bite women's ankles, sometimes going even further than that.</seg>
<seg id="61">Janet Street-Porter and the actress Maria Aitken were particular victims.</seg>
<seg id="62">It was possible to call his bluff, though.</seg>
<seg id="63">He'd go up to women and say "Show us your t*ts."</seg>
<seg id="64">One woman did just that - and a very surprised Peter ran away.</seg>
<seg id="65">Sometimes he was all bluster.</seg>
<seg id="66">I'd eat with Peter as often as I could, if only to keep him distracted from upsetting the customers.</seg>
<seg id="67">When he got up to leave from lunch one day, I noticed he was limping - and there were car tyre tracks across his shoes.</seg>
<seg id="68">What happened to your feet?</seg>
<seg id="69">I asked.</seg>
<seg id="70">"A car ran over them," he said.</seg>
<seg id="71">How the car had hit his feet and missed his very prominent stomach, I don't know - but I found it funny, even though his feet hurt terribly.</seg>
<seg id="72">As I say, we didn't always get on - Peter was an irascible man - but our partnership started with great promise.</seg>
<seg id="73">In 1973, I was making a movie called The Wilby Conspiracy with Sidney Poitier.</seg>
<seg id="74">We'd been on location in Africa but were finishing the picture in London.</seg>
<seg id="75">Sidney and I used to take turns entertaining each other to dinner.</seg>
<seg id="76">While I would take him and his wife Joanna to a variety of restaurants, he would always take me and my wife Shakira to the same place.</seg>
<seg id="77">It was Odin's, a small brasserie in Marylebone.</seg>
<seg id="78">The chef there, an unknown Peter Langan, made the best mushroom pate, spinach and seafood salads and crème brulee I ever had, anywhere in the world.</seg>
<seg id="79">Ready to fill his shoes: Mel Smith died before portraying Peter Langan</seg>
<seg id="80">I used to tell Sidney that there was plenty of scope in London for a really big Parisian-style brasserie, but alas there wasn't one.</seg>
<seg id="81">We were on set one day and Sidney said: "You know the chef in that restaurant where I take you?"</seg>
<seg id="82">He'd like to open a great big brasserie but he needs someone to back him.</seg>
<seg id="83">I said I'd like to talk to him about it.</seg>
<seg id="84">So one night in Odin's, Sidney brought Peter over to our table and he asked me if it was true that I was interested in opening a French brasserie-style place, the biggest in London.</seg>
<seg id="85">I said I was.</seg>
<seg id="86">Peter asked if I had any money.</seg>
<seg id="87">"Yeah," I told him.</seg>
<seg id="88">"So let's do it," he said.</seg>
<seg id="89">Peter had found a huge site: the former home of the old Coq d'Or restaurant in Piccadilly.</seg>
<seg id="90">I put up some money.</seg>
<seg id="91">Richard Shepherd, one of London's top chefs, came on board and we three partners had a wonderful time.</seg>
<seg id="92">Peter was an inspired restaurateur.</seg>
<seg id="93">He would tell me: "The walls must talk."</seg>
<seg id="94">So the whole place was covered in pictures by his up-and-coming artist friends - people like David Hockney and Patrick Procktor, who had paid for their meals at Odin's by giving him their paintings.</seg>
<seg id="95">I had complete faith in Peter.</seg>
<seg id="96">He taught me a lot of things about running a restaurant.</seg>
<seg id="97">"Everybody in the restaurant must be able to see everybody else at all times," he told me.</seg>
<seg id="98">I asked Peter why.</seg>
<seg id="99">Because you are not coming to our restaurant on the way to the show or after the show: you are the show.</seg>
<seg id="100">When you walk in, you are the star.</seg>
<seg id="101">When you sit down, you are the audience.</seg>
<seg id="102">When he wanted to site the bar right inside the front door, I said it would be too crowded there.</seg>
<seg id="103">He said: "You want a restaurant that looks busy."</seg>
<seg id="104">You don't want to walk into an empty room.</seg>
<seg id="105">After a shaky start (we were being robbed blind by some of our staff), the restaurant became incredibly successful from a social point of view, and it was full of stars.</seg>
<seg id="106">I brought my friends from the movie business.</seg>
<seg id="107">I wanted them to be there because it was my restaurant, as well.</seg>
<seg id="108">But a lot of people came to see Peter at his best (or worst!), and I could always see disappointment on their faces on the nights he wasn't there.</seg>
<seg id="109">Peter always liked a drink.</seg>
<seg id="110">He was a very bright man, but people only saw him drunk - and when people are drunk they seem stupid.</seg>
<seg id="111">But Peter was far from that.</seg>
<seg id="112">In those early days, he was very professional and often only pretending to be drunk.</seg>
<seg id="113">Richard remembers arriving at the door of the restaurant with Peter, who was stone-cold sober.</seg>
<seg id="114">He turned to Richard and said, "Showtime," then fell through the doors on to the floor, where he remained for half an hour.</seg>
<seg id="115">It was all for show then - but near the end, it was no act.</seg>
<seg id="116">He'd wanted to open a Langan's in Los Angeles, but I didn't want to be part of it.</seg>
<seg id="117">Peter was so enraged that he retaliated by removing my window table from the London restaurant!</seg>
<seg id="118">It ended in tragedy in 1988, when Peter was only 47.</seg>
<seg id="119">With his lifestyle perhaps it was inevitable; but it was sad, and terrible, nevertheless.</seg>
<seg id="120">Depressed at the collapse of his marriage to his wife, Susan, he tried to set fire to her, and himself, in the bedroom of their Essex home.</seg>
<seg id="121">She escaped by jumping into the garden from the first-floor balcony, but Peter suffered burns and smoke inhalation and died six weeks later.</seg>
<seg id="122">I sold my share of Langan's to Richard Shepherd in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="123">I'd done very well out of my investment, and the restaurant continues to prosper.</seg>
<seg id="124">As for making a film about those wild days: well, his life will make a great movie.</seg>
<seg id="125">But I don't know who will portray Peter now that Mel has gone.</seg>
<seg id="126">But I'd be happy to play myself.</seg>
<seg id="127">I'm rather good at that.</seg>
<seg id="128">Sir Michael Caine was talking to John McEntee</seg>
</doc>
