<seg id="16">That phrase, savage casting, probably resonates so strongly with me because here Kacey plays a boy who has virtually brought himself up; he is like a wolf-child of the housing projects.</seg>
<seg id="17">Simon, aged 12, lives with his feckless elder sister, Louise (Lea Seydoux).</seg>
<seg id="18">She makes some show of looking after him but is incapable of holding down a job or, for that matter, turning down a man; Simon, by default, has become the family breadwinner.</seg>
<seg id="19">As capable and resolute as Louise is restless and wanton, he has trained himself as a thief.</seg>
<seg id="20">Meier, 41, was born in France near the Swiss border and grew up in Switzerland.</seg>
<seg id="21">Simon's stamping ground is a ski-field similar to the ones where she spent much of her childhood.</seg>
<seg id="22">Each day he rides the cable car from the drab industrial town in the valley up to the ski-field to pilfer clothes and skis he sells to mates or through bent adults, often for absurdly small sums; to his friends in the dingy apartment block where he lives, he is a kind of Robin Hood.</seg>
<seg id="23">Mont Blanc soars in the distance but Meier and her exceptional photographer, Agnes Godard, avert the camera's gaze.</seg>
<seg id="24">The grandeur of the mountains is not their subject, any more than the glamour of sleek bourgeois families at play appeals to them, except for the purposes of grim comparison.</seg>
<seg id="25">Instead they show us the ski station as a workplace, where foreign cooks turn out meals in slush-bound kitchens and cable-car operators shower in sweaty locker rooms.</seg>
<seg id="26">"We didn't want to show how rich it is, how beautiful," Meier says.</seg>
<seg id="27">We are seeing it from the view of this little worker ant, who is in the toilet.</seg>
<seg id="28">This film, like Home, is preoccupied with space; how spaces are defined and how they define us.</seg>
<seg id="29">In Home, a rural family is effectively besieged when an abandoned highway built next to their house is suddenly opened to traffic; their response is to build a wall and huddle behind it.</seg>
<seg id="30">Godard's camera angles ensure that we never see what is on the other side of the road and that the road appears to continue endlessly in both directions.</seg>
<seg id="31">Our eye swivels back and forth across the horizontal, from which there is no escape.</seg>
<seg id="32">Home is clearly a modern fable, although the original spark for the story was real enough: Meier spotted a family eating in their garden right next to a highway in the middle of France and wondered "How can they live like that?"</seg>
<seg id="33">"It's really a mix between reality and my imagination," she says.</seg>
<seg id="34">I wrote the script as an anti-road movie, as a metaphor for people who want to live outside the walls but at the same time need them.</seg>
<seg id="35">Sister, by contrast, is defined by verticality; Simon is constantly on the move between a valley polluted by factory fumes and the crisp air of the mountains that the rich can afford to breathe.</seg>
<seg id="36">Meier shot a film for television in this valley in 2002 and "the setting stayed in my heart," she says.</seg>
<seg id="37">You have this industrial plain and you just have to look up and there is another world with this ski resort.</seg>
<seg id="38">It's very simple: this vertical view tells us a lot of things about our contemporary world, about up and down.</seg>
<seg id="39">Critics have compared Sister with films by Belgian filmmakers the Dardenne brothers, whose intimately naturalistic films give such dignity to characters who are usually downtrodden and sometimes despicable.</seg>
<seg id="40">Meier admires the Dardennes, but sees her work as very different: implicitly political rather than socially observant and too fanciful to be classed as realism.</seg>
<seg id="41">"All my characters in Home and in Sister think that they can live outside of the world with their own law, their own Utopia," she says.</seg>
<seg id="42">For the purposes of storytelling, she lets them do that.</seg>
<seg id="43">In Sister, there is no police, there is no social worker: they're already out of the world.</seg>
<seg id="44">They're very marginal, of course.</seg>
<seg id="45">And at the beginning, this balance works for them.</seg>
<seg id="46">Sister is grounded in a real remembered moment, however, just as Home was.</seg>
<seg id="47">When Meier was learning to ski on the slopes near Geneva, her instructor warned the children against a young boy hanging around on his own who was known to be stealing.</seg>
<seg id="48">"I was very surprised because he didn't look so different from us and to ski, it's expensive and still he stole," she says.</seg>
<seg id="49">My imagination went to work.</seg>
<seg id="50">I thought 'Who is this little boy?</seg>
<seg id="51">Why does he need to steal?</seg>
<seg id="52">In the end, he was banned from the resort.</seg>
<seg id="53">Kacey had difficulties accepting a character who stole, she says; similarly, Seydoux was angry with the idea of a woman who kept running out on a child.</seg>
<seg id="54">The challenge is that we love her in the end, we don't hate her, because she is a terrible mother.</seg>
<seg id="55">She was very angry with the character, but I showed her films of Agnes Varda like Vagabonde; at one moment she had a big leap and understood the character so well she started fighting for her.</seg>
<seg id="56">I was very moved.</seg>
<seg id="57">It was very important for me that the spectator can feel her pain and sense of failure.</seg>
<seg id="58">It is testimony to Meier's mastery that she is able to attract actors of the calibre of Huppert, Seydoux and Gillian Anderson - who plays "The English Lady" in Sister - to play demanding roles in small films.</seg>
<seg id="59">Seydoux, who now seems ubiquitous, was shooting pick-ups for Mission Impossible: Ghost Protocol with Tom Cruise in tandem with Sister and had to keep flying to Toronto.</seg>
<seg id="60">Meier found the positive in her absences, which distressed Kacey; she says it was as if, like Louise, Seydoux kept trying to escape her life in the film.</seg>
<seg id="61">"It was difficult to shoot like that," she says.</seg>
<seg id="62">But at the same time it was just like the character, so it was great.</seg>
<seg id="63">■ Sister is in selected release.</seg>
</doc>
