<seg id="1">Ashes UK view: English press in mixed reaction to side's poor start</seg>
<seg id="2">England is no closer to finding the final member of its pace attack for the first Ashes Test after the three leading candidates failed to fire on the opening day of its tour match against a WACA Chairman's XI side.</seg>
<seg id="3">England paceman Chris Tremlett didn't exactly push his Test claims on Thursday.</seg>
<seg id="4">THE browbeatings delivered by England's cricketers in recent years has been matched in intensity only by the chest-beating of their travelling media contingent.</seg>
<seg id="5">No group has revelled in Australia's Ashes misfortunes quite like the Pommy press over three successive victorious campaigns.</seg>
<seg id="6">But is sentiment finally changing?</seg>
<seg id="7">The triumphant headlines that accompanied England's recent 3-0 defeat of Australia have been replaced with far more cautious musings of late.</seg>
<seg id="8">And the tone of articles emanating from the WACA Ground this week have been distinctly light on jingoism and heavy on pessimism after a lamentable day in the field.</seg>
<seg id="9">The Western Australia Chair XI, comprised of second-tier players from around the country, advanced to 4-369 at stumps.</seg>
<seg id="10">The top four all passed 50, with Queenslander Chris Lynn's dashing 104 from 124 deliveries the highlight.</seg>
<seg id="11">England's armada of towering quicks struggled in Perth.</seg>
<seg id="12">Chris Tremlett, Boyd Rankin and Steve Finn all conceded runs at more than four-per-over and found wickets elusive in the extreme.</seg>
<seg id="13">"No need to panic, they insist, but the start of England's tour had grim parallels with the dark and disastrous days of the 1990s," wrote John Etheridge in The Sun.</seg>
<seg id="14">"Memorably, back in 1998 after England endured a poor day in the opening match of that winter's tour Down Under, assistant-coach Bob Cottam admitted "the wheels have come off."</seg>
<seg id="15">We have not remotely reached that stage - not that anybody in the current management would admit it - but captain Alastair Cook and head coach Andy Flower will demand a sharp improvement in the bowling.</seg>
<seg id="16">No need for panic, yet.</seg>
<seg id="17">Paul Newman, of the Daily Mail, was equally unimpressed with England's first outing of the 2013-14 Ashes tour.</seg>
<seg id="18">England's pace attack has struggled to find its groove on the opening day of its warm-up fixture against a WACA Chairman's XI side, claiming just one scalp in the opening two sessions in Perth.</seg>
<seg id="19">"The the first day of the Ashes tour here in Perth turned into a chastening experience for those looking to prove their worth for Brisbane," Newman wrote.</seg>
<seg id="20">A tour which England hope will culminate in an historic fourth successive Ashes triumph could not have got off to a worse start as a Western Australian XI cobbled together from those not considered good enough for their Sheffield Shield team flogged England to all parts of the WACA.</seg>
<seg id="21">Long day in the field for England.</seg>
<seg id="22">The sentiment was hardly brighter in the Guardian, where Andy Wilson pondered over England's "chastening" start to the tour and wondered aloud whether the tourists had been caught out in fielding three towering quicks on a "slow and even stodgy" WACA Ground pitch.</seg>
<seg id="23">Tall guys or fall guys?</seg>
<seg id="24">Chris Tremlett and Steven Finn may have prospered in Perth during England's last Ashes tour, encouraging the management to include a third giant, Boyd Rankin, in this squad, and to select all three for this opening fixture at the famously fast and bouncy Waca," Wilson wrote.</seg>
<seg id="25">But after a chastening opening day in which Tremlett, Finn and Rankin recorded combined figures of one for 245 from 53 overs on an unexpectedly slow and even stodgy surface, they were warned to expect similar conditions for the Perth date in this series, the third Test in mid-December.</seg>
<seg id="26">WACA deck may be same for Test.</seg>
<seg id="27">Irrespective of the surface Dean Wilson, writing in The Mirror, noted: "England's collection of six foot eight quickies could and should have done better."</seg>
<seg id="28">More expected from pace trio.</seg>
