<seg id="2">NEW YORK (Reuters) - The U.S. decision to allow greater use of electronic devices on flights is "another favorable tailwind" for Gogo Inc., the internet provider for 80 percent of the U.S. commercial aircraft fleet, its chief executive told Reuters on Thursday.</seg>
<seg id="3">"If people have their device out, it's much more likely they'll use it," CEO Michael Small said in an interview.</seg>
<seg id="4">Small said the Federal Aviation Administration rules won't generate a significant short-term revenue increase for Gogo,</seg>
<seg id="5">But the move, announced by the announced by FAA administrator Michael Huerta, could yield benefits over the long term if the U.S. move is followed by other nations' regulators, Small said.</seg>
