<seg id="1">Controversy over Venice theme park plan</seg>
<seg id="2">But critics say that Venice has already become enough of a de facto cultural theme park as it is, with locals moving away in droves, greengrocers and bakeries being pushed out by trinket shops and tourism dominating the city's economy.</seg>
<seg id="3">The environmental rehabilitation of San Biagio should go ahead, but it must be done with respect for this city.</seg>
<seg id="4">"Venice is not a theme park, and everyone must take account of that," Giorgio Orsoni, the mayor of Venice, said.</seg>
<seg id="5">I've been informed of the project and it does raise some concerns, above all because of the plan to build the large Ferris wheel.</seg>
<seg id="6">Venice, which has a population of around 60,000, is swamped by the same number of tourists every day.</seg>
<seg id="7">That adds up to a total of 22 million visitors a year.</seg>
<seg id="8">This week a former mayor of the city revived the idea, first mooted three decades ago, of limiting the number of visitors able to enter the city with some sort of ticket system.</seg>
<seg id="9">"I started to look at the possibility when I was mayor, but it would be much easier now, with more modern technology, to introduce a system to control visitor numbers," Paolo Costa, who is now the president of Venice's port authority, told La Repubblica newspaper.</seg>
<seg id="10">The idea came to me again during a visit to China when I looked around and thought, if only a fraction of this great mass of humanity jumps on a plane to Venice, what will happen then?</seg>
<seg id="11">But Angela Vettese, an official in charge of tourism, said limiting numbers would be "anti-democratic" and suggested instead efforts to direct tourists away from saturated sites such as the Rialto Bridge and St Mark's Square to lesser known corners of the lagoon city.</seg>
<seg id="12">"If we introduced entrance tickets, it would only enforce the impression that Venice is a theme park," she said.</seg>
<seg id="13">Concern over the strangulation of Venice by mass tourism, including the thousands of visitors who are disgorged each week from cruise ships, led the World Monuments Fund to include Venice on its most recent list of at-risk heritage sites.</seg>
<seg id="14">The city was threatened by "large-scale cruise-ship tourism," which had increased in scale by 400 per cent just in the last five years, said Bonnie Burnham, president of the organisation, earlier this month.</seg>
<seg id="15">Florence has a similar problem to Venice - 16 million tourists descend on the Tuscan city each year but they congregate in two or three hugely popular spots, such as the Ponte Vecchio, the Uffizi Gallery and the Duomo, or cathedral.</seg>
<seg id="16">A modern-day Medici prince, a descendant of the famous Florentine family, said mass tourism is such a threat to the city that it should be put on a Unesco list of endangered World Heritage sites.</seg>
<seg id="17">"The economy of the city is gravely suffering because the itineraries created by international tour operators are conditioning visitors to spend an average of two nights and just one full day of sightseeing in the city centre, usually in a very restricted area," said Prince Ottaviano de" Medici in a statement.</seg>
<seg id="18">This means that while a handful of streets are literally invaded by millions of tourists, the rest of the city centre of Florence remains virtually deserted and the majority of museums almost totally unvisited.</seg>
<seg id="19">The prince, the representative of the Medici family, said while the city centre was thriving on the back of tourism, other parts of Florence were in serious economic decline.</seg>
<seg id="20">That has caused dramatic population decline - in the 20 years between 1981 and 2001, a fifth of Florentines left the city, he said.</seg>
<seg id="21">The normal daily life of the city was also being damaged by "semi-permanent camps of gypsies in the city centre, (groups of) drunken people, the invasion of fast-food restaurants and small shops managed by multi-ethnic migrants."</seg>
<seg id="22">Prince de" Medici has set up a campaign, the Save Florence Project, and sent a petition to Unesco representatives in Italy calling for urgent action to safeguard the centuries-old character of the city centre.</seg>
</doc>
