<seg id="1">What the Chefs Daniel Patterson and Gabrielle Hamilton Talk About at Dinner: The New Yorker</seg>
<seg id="2">On a recent wet evening, Daniel Patterson, the chef of the two-Michelin-star San Francisco restaurant Coi, showed up at the 92nd Street Y to be interviewed by his old friend Gabrielle Hamilton, the chef of the cozy, rib-sticking East Village restaurant Prune.</seg>
<seg id="3">Patterson was there to discuss his new book, "Coi: Stories and Recipes," an ode to the restaurant, to Northern California, and to the eleven-course tasting menu.</seg>
<seg id="4">"I love the way they flow, the elegance of form, the element of surprise," he writes.</seg>
<seg id="5">Within haute cuisine, they allow for the highest level of expression.</seg>
<seg id="6">"I'm done with tasting menus," said Hamilton, a few minutes in.</seg>
<seg id="7">"That's like saying, "You can write a perfectly good short story, why would you ever write a novel?," " Patterson pounced.</seg>
<seg id="8">"We're arguing!" crowed Hamilton, then gestured to the event organizers.</seg>
<seg id="9">I told them there would be arguing.</seg>
<seg id="10">The two made an unlikely pair.</seg>
<seg id="11">Hamilton, forty-seven, is known for her memoir, "Blood, Bones & Butter," a rollicking, intensely honest story that includes her early-career drug use, her lesbianism, her troubled marriage to an Italian doctor who needed a green card, and, on the plus side, the opening of her now-beloved restaurant.</seg>
<seg id="12">Patterson, forty-five, known for his perfectly executed dishes, which are often plated with tweezers, was fresh off a plane on one leg of a many-legged book tour.</seg>
<seg id="13">Trim, ascetic, and measured in both movement and judgment, he seemed both there and not there - as if he were sitting just six inches to the left of himself and observing his own being.</seg>
<seg id="14">Patterson has written a new kind of cookbook.</seg>
<seg id="15">Its three hundred and three pages follow a loose format - one page with a story and a through-written recipe with no measurements and, on the facing page, a striking photo of the dish.</seg>
<seg id="16">The writing, like his food, is precise, beautiful, and a bit meditative.</seg>
<seg id="17">Take his mini-treatise on seasoning:</seg>
<seg id="18">When you're in the kitchen tasting, think about the aftertaste.</seg>
<seg id="19">If it seems to fade, to just drop away on the finish, that usually means that there's not enough salt ....</seg>
<seg id="20">If the salt is a tiny bit high, a few drops of lemon juice can bring it down.</seg>
<seg id="21">If the acidity is high, it could need a little more sweetness.</seg>
<seg id="22">A few grains of salt here or a drop of vinegar there, those are the kinds of little adjustments that make good food great.</seg>
<seg id="23">Six months of culinary school distilled into one lovely paragraph.</seg>
<seg id="24">While Hamilton's cooking is also precise, to say that Patterson's restaurant is just as approachable as hers is like saying that his lichen-crusted beef - step one: scrape lichen off of trees in a forest - would make a perfect weeknight dinner.</seg>
<seg id="25">As Hamilton writes in her book, of the beginning days of Prune, "There would be no foam and no "conceptual" or "intellectual" food; just the salty, sweet, starchy, brothy, crispy things that one craves when one is actually hungry."</seg>
<seg id="26">Patterson calls it squab; she calls it pigeon.</seg>
<seg id="27">Patterson not only runs four establishments in the Bay Area but also frequently travels the world to speak at food symposiums and meet up with an unofficial culinary boys" club that includes Ferran Adrià, David Chang, and Rene Redzepi.</seg>
<seg id="28">He told the room of about fifty attendees that, by necessity, he'd written the book in six months and edited it in three.</seg>
<seg id="29">"Once, on a ten-hour flight from San Francisco to Monaco, I wrote fifteen thousand words," he said.</seg>
<seg id="30">At least two audience members scribbled down long division on the back of a flyer that had been placed on each seat.</seg>
<seg id="31">That translated to approximately six double-spaced pages an hour.</seg>
<seg id="32">There was a long beat.</seg>
<seg id="33">Were you taking performance-enhancing drugs?</seg>
<seg id="34">Hamilton asked.</seg>
<seg id="35">A few attendees giggled.</seg>
<seg id="36">Patterson smiled thinly.</seg>
<seg id="37">In the course of the hour-long talk, the two discussed the writing process, their trouble finding good line cooks, and the restaurateur Joe Bastianich, who claimed to have invented the everything bagel in his memoir, "Restaurant Man."</seg>
<seg id="38">"I fucking love that!" said Hamilton.</seg>
<seg id="39">I'm claiming eggs at dinner.</seg>
<seg id="40">I did that.</seg>
<seg id="41">"What are you going to "Joe Bastinaich"?"</seg>
<seg id="42">I'm making it a verb.</seg>
<seg id="43">I'm thinking brain mayo.</seg>
<seg id="44">"Brainaise," Patterson offered, quietly.</seg>
<seg id="45">He dodged the question until finally he asked, "Can I claim having a two-Michelin-star restaurant next to a strip club?"</seg>
<seg id="46">Coi is located in a seedy part of the North Beach neighborhood, just up the street from City Lights Books.</seg>
<seg id="47">Hamilton approved.</seg>
<seg id="48">A half hour later, the two chefs crammed into a tiny table at Sushi of Gari, on Seventy-eighth street.</seg>
<seg id="49">The waiter offered an omakase menu, a tasting menu of sorts.</seg>
<seg id="50">Unsurprisingly, Patterson voted yes and, surprisingly, so did Hamilton.</seg>
<seg id="51">The first plate included a few pieces of intensely cold, crunchy celery.</seg>
<seg id="52">Hamilton asked the waiter how it was made, and retrieved a pen and a pink notebook from her bag.</seg>
<seg id="53">"It's pickled celery," the waiter said, unhelpfully.</seg>
<seg id="54">Patterson stepped in: "It's rice-wine vinegar and salt."</seg>
<seg id="55">I think it's a pour-over, because I could feel just a little softening.</seg>
<seg id="56">Hamilton nodded and scribbled something in her notebook.</seg>
<seg id="57">The subject turned to the international culinary symposiums that Patterson attends, which often tackle lofty topics, like authenticity and the food system.</seg>
<seg id="58">"I don't like talking about food beyond "I'm hungry and I want something delicious to eat," " said Hamilton, popping a piece of salmon sushi into her mouth.</seg>
<seg id="59">To the delight of both chefs, the waiter, with gravitas, had described it as "salmon with sautéed tomato and a little onion saying "hello" from the side."</seg>
<seg id="60">That's such a cop out!</seg>
<seg id="61">Patterson retorted.</seg>
<seg id="62">He noted the ideas, collaboration, and deep friendships that came out of the symposiums, and out of the culinary retreats, called Cook it Raw, that the boys" club takes to remote places, like Lapland, where they cook together, bond, and share ideas.</seg>
<seg id="63">I so want to get an invite!</seg>
<seg id="64">Hamilton said.</seg>
<seg id="65">"One dish I made was out over this open fire, and I wanted to work with beets," Patterson recalled, picking up a piece of ebi sushi with his hands.</seg>
<seg id="66">He cooked the beets slowly for six hours, moving them around the fire every twenty minutes or so, giving the root a super-sweet, juicy, quality.</seg>
<seg id="67">"So I made this sauce with beet juice and thickened it with reindeer blood," he continued.</seg>
<seg id="68">"Because it's the same color, right, of course," Hamilton interjected, laughing.</seg>
<seg id="69">As the final dish came out, the topic returned to the tasting menu.</seg>
<seg id="70">"It's just that I don't want to go to an hors-d'oeuvres party for four hours," said Hamilton.</seg>
<seg id="71">But certain content only comes in certain formats!</seg>
<seg id="72">As they waited for the check, Hamilton picked up the book, which she'd brought after the talk, and started flipping through.</seg>
<seg id="73">It's just so beautiful, though.</seg>
<seg id="74">It really made me want to come to Coi.</seg>
<seg id="75">Wait, she was anti-tasting menu but had not yet tasted Patterson's raison d"être?</seg>
<seg id="76">"I know, I know," she said, taking in an overhead shot of chilled, spiced ratatouille soup that looked like a painting, three swirls of color - beige, red, and yellow - zipping around a mound of perfectly cubed vegetables.</seg>
<seg id="77">"O.K. Yours is the only tasting menu I will eat," she relented.</seg>
<seg id="78">Patterson smiled.</seg>
<seg id="79">Then they paid the check and headed out onto the wet streets, in search of Negronis.</seg>
<seg id="80">Read Gabrielle Hamilton's sidebar in the magazine this week, "Family Meal."</seg>
<seg id="81">Above: Gabrielle Hamilton.</seg>
