<seg id="1">GCSE reforms: pupils to be graded from one to nine</seg>
<seg id="2">This includes:</seg>
<seg id="3">A cut in the amount of coursework and ensuring that any remaining tasks are marked by external examiners rather than teachers to avoid over-generous grading;</seg>
<seg id="4">A greater focus on end-of-course tests - scraping bite-sized modular exams;</seg>
<seg id="5">A single assessment window in May and June to stop exams being sat through the year;</seg>
<seg id="6">The end of "tiered" papers - easy and hard exams for pupils of differing ability levels - in most subjects other than maths.</seg>
<seg id="7">The changes will be applied to new GCSEs in English literature, English language and maths being introduced from September 2015.</seg>
<seg id="8">They will be applied to other core subjects a year later.</seg>
<seg id="9">Ofqual also confirmed that it would consult on the range of subjects that will carry the GCSE title in the future.</seg>
<seg id="10">The move is likely to fuel speculation that some "soft" subjects such as media studies, PE and drama will no longer be branded as GCSEs.</seg>
<seg id="11">Glenys Stacey, the chief regulator said: "The evidence is clear: GCSEs need to change if they are to remain respected qualifications and support a world class education system."</seg>
<seg id="12">In recent years we have been taking action to improve the current GCSEs.</seg>
<seg id="13">But further changes are needed if GCSEs are to be more engaging and worthwhile to teach and study.</seg>
<seg id="14">GCSEs were introduced by the Conservatives in the late 80s to replace O-levels.</seg>
<seg id="15">Pupils were originally graded on a seven-point scale from A to G.</seg>
<seg id="16">An A* grade was added in 1994 - creating an eight-point structure - amid fears that exams failed to properly mark out the very brightest pupils.</seg>
<seg id="17">Today, Ofqual confirmed that it would ditch the system altogether in favour of one based on numbers for the new GCSE qualifications.</seg>
<seg id="18">In a key change, pupils will be graded on a nine-point scale, with nine being the highest grade.</seg>
<seg id="19">This will allow examiners to add more numbers in the future if further discrimination is needed.</seg>
<seg id="20">The nine point system will "provide more differentiation between students achieving the middle and higher grades," Ofqual said.</seg>
<seg id="21">It will also enable employers to differentiate between GCSEs sat in England and different GCSEs taken by pupils in Wales and Northern Ireland, which are not adopting the changes.</seg>
<seg id="22">Ms Stacey added: "For many people, the move away from traditional grades, A, B,C and so on, may be hard to understand."</seg>
<seg id="23">But it is important.</seg>
<seg id="24">The new qualifications will be significantly different and we need to signal this clearly.</seg>
<seg id="25">It will be fairer to all students that users of the qualification will be able to see immediately whether they did the new or a previous version of the GCSE.</seg>
<seg id="26">The new scale will also allow better discrimination between the higher performing students.</seg>
</doc>
