<seg id="1">Leaving formula</seg>
<seg id="2">"I definitely cannot switch off the tap in terms of racing" â€¦ Mark Webber.</seg>
<seg id="3">Photo: Neale Haynes</seg>
<seg id="4">In a world dominated by ego - where an elite group of men are compensated for risking their lives every second weekend by the trappings of wealth, glamour and fame - the down-to-earth Mark Webber doesn't fit the stereotype of a formula one playboy.</seg>
<seg id="5">But he certainly looks like one; his sunken cheeks further pronouncing his chiselled jaw-line, his trademark dark stubble contrasting against his gleaming white smile, his lean marathon-runner frame.</seg>
<seg id="6">During a recent visit to Sydney from his UK base in Buckinghamshire, he meets me wearing a light grey shirt, rolled-up sleeves, sneakers and casual- fit jeans.</seg>
<seg id="7">"G'day, mate," he says with the twang of an outback publican, despite having lived in Europe since leaving his home town of Queanbeyan at 18 to chase a boyhood dream of racing.</seg>
<seg id="8">Webber initially struggled to climb out of the junior ranks, battling against a lack of support from corporate Australia and a tide of wealthy European kids whose parents could buy their way into the best teams.</seg>
<seg id="9">But his self-belief - and the faith of his manager and partner Ann Neal - remained, and Webber eventually fought his way into formula one.</seg>
<seg id="10">There, for the past 11 years, he has become one of Australia's most successful grand prix drivers (behind only former world champions Sir Jack Brabham and Alan Jones) with nine victories, 39 podiums and 12 pole positions from a total of 214 grand prix starts.</seg>
<seg id="11">After November 24, however, Webber will no longer be a formula one driver.</seg>
<seg id="12">The Brazilian Grand Prix will be his final race at the pinnacle of motorsport.</seg>
<seg id="13">Unlike some of his past rivals - including the seven-time world champion, Michael Schumacher, whose three-year return to racing tarnished his legendary status - Webber is retiring on his own terms with the knowledge that his motivation has peaked, his youthful fearlessness has waned and, since the introduction a few years ago of tyres designed to wear out quickly, the challenge and exhilaration of driving a grand prix car has been eroded.</seg>
<seg id="14">"I have never struggled with motivation and I couldn't comprehend how other athletes were saying they had to keep their motivation to remain on the highest stage," he says.</seg>
<seg id="15">I thought, 'What the hell, how could you lose your motivation?'</seg>
<seg id="16">But then you start to think, 'Well I've done this a long time and I'm going through the drill of it all again; the never-ending travel and watching my weight for 11 months of the year.'</seg>
<seg id="17">It gets harder and harder.</seg>
<seg id="18">No one else can do the training but me.</seg>
<seg id="19">No one else has to refuse that dessert but me.</seg>
<seg id="20">That has been endless, and it gets to you after a while.</seg>
<seg id="21">Outside observers of the sport may speculate that Webber's fractious relationship with his German team mate - three-time world champion Sebastian Vettel - played a part in his decision to walk away.</seg>
<seg id="22">The pair have clashed on and off the track for the past six years, starting and finishing with Vettel stealing almost certain victories from the Australian; the first when the German crashed into Webber while driving behind a safety car in torrential rain during the 2007 Japanese Grand Prix and the latter during this year's Malaysian Grand Prix, when Vettel disobeyed team instructions and overtook Webber to win the race.</seg>
<seg id="23">But although he admits Vettel will likely never make his Christmas card list, you get the sense that he enjoyed being challenged - mentally, physically and emotionally - by the German, and leaves formula one a stronger and faster driver than he would have been otherwise.</seg>
<seg id="24">"I think I will be remembered as someone who was pretty hard yet fair on the circuit and made his presence felt," he says.</seg>
<seg id="25">You could call me a 'nearly man', as I could have certainly got a bit more out of my career.</seg>
<seg id="26">But I think most people will look at me as a pretty fair competitor - that's how I want to be remembered.</seg>
<seg id="27">He has relished the camaraderie with his team mates who have stood by him through his racing career.</seg>
<seg id="28">We've had some good fights - off and on the track ...</seg>
<seg id="29">It's been a journey from boys to men; I will miss some of that.</seg>
<seg id="30">But nothing is forever, so you have to move on to the next chapter.</seg>
<seg id="31">Having not been forced into retirement, either through lack of results or injury, Webber is still a highly regarded property.</seg>
<seg id="32">He was courted to join Fernando Alonso at Ferrari for this season, but "we couldn't agree on the terms," and was likely to be offered another contract with Red Bull for next season.</seg>
<seg id="33">That was before he handed in his resignation on the eve of this year's British Grand Prix at the Silverstone circuit, giving his team boss just five minutes notice that he had signed a deal to lead Porsche's return to the famous Le Mans 24-hour sports car race from next year.</seg>
<seg id="34">Both were brave and bullish moves; the former an obvious retaliation for being treated with such disrespect at the same venue two years earlier, when he won the first of his two British GPs despite Vettel receiving preferential treatment; the latter sees Webber return to the famous French racetrack that almost claimed his life in 1999 when his Mercedes sports car flipped into the air, on two separate occasions, at more than 350km/h.</seg>
<seg id="35">"The sports cars at the time were super dangerous, as there were a lot of cars flipping, but I can't wrap myself in cotton wool," he says.</seg>
<seg id="36">I definitely cannot switch off the tap in terms of the whole racing aspect and getting my feet out of bed with that competitive urge ...</seg>
<seg id="37">I know it will have to end one day, but there's still plenty left in me.</seg>
<seg id="38">He's looking forward to spending more time with family in Australia, to "give a bit back, because it's been pretty selfish over the past 15 years - it's been all about me - and I can switch it off a little now."</seg>
<seg id="39">Not completely ... but just a little bit.</seg>
</doc>
