<seg id="1">Banksy's 'vandalised' oil painting raises $615,000 for charity</seg>
<seg id="2">A painting that British street artist Banksy originally bought for $50 (£31) in a New York charity shop has now been sold, after he made his own marks on it, for $615,000 (£383,400) in an online auction after 138 bids.</seg>
<seg id="3">The profits will go to homeless charity Housing Works in the city.</seg>
<seg id="4">Banksy first revealed the piece, which he called The Banality of The Banality of Evil, on Tuesday in the Housing Works store on New York's 23rd Street where he originally bought it before adding a Nazi officer sitting on a bench facing the bucolic landscape scene.</seg>
<seg id="5">The painting was anonymously donated to the charity shop, and staff received a phone call shortly after that explainting its authenticity.</seg>
<seg id="6">Part of Banksy's month-long residency in New York, where the artist unveiled a new piece everyday, The Banality of The Banality of Evil was explained on his website as "a thrift store painting vandalised then re-donated to the thrift store."</seg>
<seg id="7">He announced he would auction it the next day, and the sale closed on Thursday night.</seg>
<seg id="8">Housing Works officials are yet to verify the final bid, but have said that "100 per cent of the proceeds from the auction will go towards lifesaving services for people living with and effected by HIV/AIDS, including housing, medical care, job training, legal services, and case management."</seg>
